    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Steel rebar is essential because concrete, while excellent in compression, is quite weak when it comes to tension. It's like trying to hold a heavy load with just a pile of brittle, slightly crumbly mud—it cracks easily under pulling forces. The steel rebar, on the other hand, is incredibly strong in tension, making it the perfect partner for the concrete. This combination, known as reinforced concrete, allows the foundation to handle both pushing (compression) and pulling (tension) forces simultaneously.",
      "source": "target",
